@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@prev "Copyright"
@next "Requirements"

                              @{b}Introduction@{ub}
                          ====================

Mouse Control was inspired by AirLink (aka InfraRexx) by Leon Woestenberg and 
Jeroen Steeblik and brought to the masses by CU-Amiga magazine. Basically it
sits in the background waiting for you to send it some @{"ARexx" link "ARexx" 0} command to perform 
some action or other on the mouse pointer. This ARexx command can be supplied by AirLink - hence a 
remote control mouse. That's it really. Not particularly useful as it can be a bit slow (but this is
avoidable with care) but maybe useable as a presentation tool. 
Hmm, maybe I should do a demo ARexx script for that...

If you can think of any other use for this, then please do tell me.

Mouse Control was written in Blitz Basic 2.1

                                                 Roger Light

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Introduction"

                             @{b}Requirements@{ub}
                         ====================


    You need to have ARexx running to use Mouse Control. Other than that
    I think any Amiga with WB 2.04 (v37) or higher should be OK. Can't test
    it mind you ;)

    Also, I suppose a working AirLink/InfraRexx would be a bonus if you're 
    going to use it as a remote controlled mouse. 

    If you intend to do recording of tapes, you will need the appropriate 
    amount of memory and hard drive / floppy space. I doubt this would be a 
    problem, even for 512k users... See @{"technical" link "Technical",0}.

@endnode

