@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "ARexx"
@prev "Installation"

                                 @{b}Usage@{ub}
                             =============

Mouse Control should be started from the CLI. If you want it to start each time
you reboot, put it in your user-startup with eg 'run <>nil: mouse_control'. 
Mouse Control can only be run once.
Command line argument is as below.

Mouse_Control
DIS=DISTANCE/N,INC=INCREMENT/N,SIZE/N,NEG/S,SAVEDIR/K

      o  DISTANCE is the pixels that the mouse will move by, by default when a
   movement command is called. Default=10

      o INCREMENT is the amount of pixels that will be added/subtracted onto 
   distance when the appropriate ARexx commands are called. Default=5

      o SIZE is the size of the memory buffer (bytes) that recording will be 
   stored to. You MUST have enough free memory to cater for this value.
   Also, if you want to save the tape to disk, then you must have this 
   amount of disk space. Also, must be >8. (See @{"technical" link "Technical",0}.Default=1024b

      o  NEG is a switch that, if set, will allow distance to become negative
   as it is decremented. If it is not set, distance will stop at 0.
   (With negative distances up=down and left=right)

      o SAVEDIR is the directory that the tapes will be saved/loaded in.
   MUST end with a ':' or a '/'. Default='s:'

For example:

mouse_control DIS=10 NEG

mouse_control INC=1 SIZE=500 SAVEDIR=HD1:tapes/

For loading and saving in the current directory, use:

mouse_control SAVEDIR=



@endnode

@node "ARexx" "ARexx"
@next "Tapes"
@prev "Usage"

                            @{b}ARexx Interface@{ub}
                        =======================

Mouse Control has a fairly extensive ARexx interface. Any functions 
that you'd like to see here, please do get in touch with @{"me" link "Author" 0}.

Mouse Control opens up a port called MOUSE_CONTROL.

Commands marked with a '*' are not available in recording of tapes (although they can be used whilst
recording).
Commands marked with a 'x' are recording commands.
Commands marked with a '+' don't work, but are included for completeness.
A more in depth discussion of recording commands can be found in @{"Tapes" link "Tapes",0}.

Commands available are as follows:

       * QUIT - quits Mouse Control.

       o NOPE - Performs No OPEration. Actually moves the mouse 0 across, 0 down.
           Useful for implementing delays in tapes.

       o UP - moves the mouse pointer up by @{"distance" link "Usage" 0} pixels.

       o UP ## - moves the mouse pointer up by ## pixels (doesn't affect distance)
      (where ## is 0 -> 32768)

       o DOWN - moves the mouse pointer down by distance pixels.
   
       o DOWN ## - moves the mouse pointer down by ## pixels.

       o RIGHT - moves the mouse pointer right by distance pixels.
   
       o RIGHT ## - moves the mouse pointer down by ## pixels.

       o LEFT - moves the mouse pointer left by distance pixels.
   
       o LEFT ## - moves the mouse pointer down by ## pixels.

       + ABSX ## - puts the pointer at the absolute position ## in the x direction.

       + ABSY ## - puts the pointer at the absolute position ## in the y direction.

       o LMB - clicks the left mouse button once.

       o LMB DOUBLE - double clicks the left mouse button.

       o LMB ON - holds down the left mouse button. (eg for dragging)

       o LMB OFF - releases the left mouse button.

       o RMB - clicks the right mouse button once.

       o RMB ON - holds down the right mouse button.

       o RMB OFF - releases the right mouse button.

       o INCREMENT ## - increases distance by ## pixels.
         (where ## is 0 -> 128)

       o INCREMENT - increases distance by @{"increment" link "Usage",0} pixels.

       o DECREMENT ## - decreases distance by ## pixels.

       o DECREMENT - decreases distance by @{"increment" link "Usage",0} pixels.

       o DISTANCE ## - sets distance to ## pixels.

       o RESET - places the mouse pointer at 0,0 on the screen (ie top left).

       o NEG - allows @{"distance" link "Usage",0} to become negative.

       o NONEG - stops distance going negative.

       x RECORD - starts the recording of mouse events. See @{"Tapes" link "Tapes",0}.

       x STOP - stops the recording of mouse event.

       x PLAY - plays back a pre-recorded set of mouse events.

       x SAVE $$ - saves a tape to location savedir:$$ (See @{"Usage" link "Usage",0}

       x LOAD $$ - loads a tape from s:$$

       x FREE - frees the tape from memory.

So, for example, if I wanted to move the mouse 7 pixels to the left, and then click
the left mouse button I could use the following script:

/* Mouse_control test script */

address mouse_control

left 7
lmb

/* End script */

If you have any questions/problems with any of these, please don't hesitate to 
contact me!

Also, see the included ARexx scripts.
@endnode

@node "Tapes" "Tapes"
@next "Technical"
@prev "ARexx"

                                   @{b}Tapes@{ub}
                               =============

With tapes, you can record a whole sequence of movements that you input through
Mouse Control so that you can save them to disk and reuse them later at any time.
This could be done with large ARexx scripts, but it would be rather tedious to set 
up, and not all that easy either.  

After you start recording, each time you send a command to Mouse Control (see {"ARexx" link "ARexx",0}
for supported commands) it records it on a tape held in memory ready to play back. 

A tape file always end in ".tape" but it isn't necessary for you to put that on either
when loading or saving them. It's more of a recognition thing.
The ARexx commands LOAD and SAVE always require a file name argument.

Playback won't happen with the same delays as occurred when the tape was being recorded,
so care should be taken with LMB clicks over a single icon that isn't supposed to be 
double clicked but may well be. Playback can only happen if recording has stopped.

Saving may take place at any time, as may loading. The tape needn't be freed if you are
loading or when quitting. If you need the memory that the tape is taking up, just free it.

If recording has been stopped, and then it is started again, the recording will commence
where it had originally started. If a tape has been loaded / freed in the time between 
stopping and starting then a new tape will be created in memory.

@endnode

@node "Technical" "Technical"
@next "FAQ"
@prev "Tapes"

                                 @{b}Technical@{ub}
                             =================

This information is provided so that manual debugging of tapes is
possible. This should now be pretty much obsolete with the advent of
Tape Editor.

When recording commences, a bank of memory is reserved for Mouse Control use. At the 
fifth byte along in this memory bank, a word (2 bytes) is placed that indicates the 
starting value of distance for the tape. Then a byte that represents the starting value
of the increment is placed, followed by a byte for the NEG switch. 0=NoNeg, -1=Neg. 
The first four bytes are reserved for the position of the last command in the tape.
This is stored as a long. 

The first command is at the 31st byte in (ie 1-30 are command bytes). This gives room 
for further expansion. Each command takes up one byte. However, those commands which take
an argument, eg UP #, use another 2 bytes after themselves to store the #. 
Each command is represented by a number as follows:

    1 = NOPE
    2 = UP
    3 = DOWN
    4 = LEFT
    5 = RIGHT
    6 = RMB ON
    7 = RMB OFF
    8 = RMB
    9 = LMB ON
   10 = LMB OFF
   11 = LMB DOUBLE
   12 = LMB
   13 = RESET
   14 = NEG
   15 = NONEG
   16 = INCREMENT
   17 = DECREMENT
   18 = UP #
   19 = DOWN #
   20 = LEFT #
   21 = RIGHT #
   22 = INCREMENT #
   23 = DECREMENT #
   24 = DISTANCE #
   25 = ABSX #
   26 = ABSY #

When playing back, any values other that these will be ignored. Also, if there are 
commands that extend beyond the address dictated by the long value at the start of the
tape then they will be ignored as well.
   
@endnode

@node "FAQ" "FAQ"
@next "To Do"
@prev "Technical"

                                 @{b}FAQ@{ub}
                             ===========

   Q - Do I need a tape recorder to record tapes? 
   A - No.

   Q - Will my ordinary mouse still work? 
   A - Yes.

   Q - What happens if I copy "foobar" to "foobar.tape" and then 
       load it into mouse_control?
   A - Try it and see. It might do something.
   
@endnode

@node "To Do" "To Do"
@next "History"
@prev "FAQ"

                                 @{b}To Do..@{ub}
                             ===============

I think I've pretty much covered everything that could be useful as far as using
the mouse goes. However, I am considering the following:

      o Adding a For..Next loop kind of thing for playing back from tapes. This
   would be best done through Tape Editor I feel, but I don't know how well it
   would work. I do have a great way of displaying it on the list view mind you.

      o @{b}Anything@{ub} that you think should be included. Subject to my being
   able to do it and it being relevant to the program. 

      o Having found out how to implement some of the functions I have used in C
   I am now going to concentrate on porting Mouse Control to C.
   What benefits will this bring you ask? Hmm, well off hand, I'll be able 
   to put in a version number, which I don't know how to implement in Blitz.
   Apart from that, I think that programming in C is generally a better thing
   to be able to do than programming in Blitz. Hopefully the executable will
   end up smaller as well!

      o SerMouse Control.

      o TCPMouse Control. Maybe. I fancy trying to play around with the TCP
   functions available in Blitz so might try and implement this as
    practise. No practical use as far as I can tell.
@endnode

@node "History" "History"
@next "Problems"
@prev "To Do"

                                 @{b}History@{ub}
                             ===============

@{b}v1.3 (5/3/99)@{ub}
      o Despite the long time since the last update, not much has been added really.
   Mouse Control now supports commands with arguments and has two new commands ABSX
   and ABSY, even though they don't work properly. Some problems have been ironed out
   as well - Mouse Control didn't tell Tape Editor that it was here properly.

@{b}v1.21 (18/12/98)@{ub}
      o Changed format of tape files slightly. Bit of tidying up after I
   went over the 30kb mark. Now back under it!
   Fixed "RMB" command which sometimes got stuck.
   If Tape Editor is running when Mouse Control is run, Mouse Control
   sends a message to say that it has been run.

@{b}v1.2 (2/12/98)@{ub}
      o As promised, the recording commands now work correctly after I put it my
   own ones ;) Improved argument handling. Some other minor changes. Addition
   of a few new commands.

@{b}v1.1 (29/11/98)@{ub}
      o New version, in light of below. Added some handy elements to the movement
   routines. You can now set distance, increment, and the amount of movement
   on a command to command basis. 
   Major addition - recording and playback of tapes! However, they Blitz's tapes
   don't work properly.

@{b}v1.01 (29/11/98)@{ub}
      o Fix of "minor" problem that made Mouse Control eat all of your memory...
   Just before I noticed this problem I made a botched attempt at uploading
   v1.0 to the Aminet (damned PC ftp clients) - thankfully it didn't work!
   Removed enforcer hit.
   Found out about InputStream by Robert Hardy. Grr. Basically it does the
   same as Mouse Control, but for windows and screens as well. Personally
   I think that Mouse Control has got some lots nicer functions for (duh) 
   controlling the mouse, but then I am biassed. Release now delayed until
   I can figure out how to do recording of scripts or something suitably 
   impressive that will make Mouse Control stand out over InputStream.

@{b}v1.0 (22/11/98)@{ub}
      o  Massive tidy up and introduction of ARexx port. (Basically just a 
   whole new program) Extra commands added.

@{b}v0.0x (~6/11/98)@{ub}
      o First try. Only used command line arguments and so had to be incurred
   each time a new movement was wanted. Not the ideal situation (imagine
   it for floppy users!) 
@endnode

@node "Problems" "Few and far between..."
@prev "History"
@next "Author"

                                @{b}Problems@{ub}
                            ================

I have been told that using one of the direction commands that takes an argument,
eg UP #, produces some interesting effects on higher resolution screens. I can't
remember which ones it was now but when I looked into at the time, there was nothing
that I could do about it. Hopefully, when I write Mouse Control in C, I will be
able to do something about it.

ABSX # and ABSY # don't work.

@endnode

